  ‚Äñ \ssection{Definition} ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ A ‚ù¨real matrix‚ù≠ (‚ù¨real-valued matrix‚ù≠, ‚ù¨matrix of real
    numbers‚ù≠, ‚ù¨matrix‚ù≠) is a two-dimensional array of real numbers. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ Recall that we are interested in solutions of the linear
    equations
    ‚óá ‚¶ä
      ‚Äñ \begin{aligned} ‚¶â

      ‚Äñ y_1 ‚ù≤&‚ù≥= A_{11}x_1 + A_{12}x_2 + ‚ãØ + A_{1n}x_n ·ú∂ ‚¶â

      ‚Äñ y_2 ‚ù≤&‚ù≥= A_{21}x_1 + A_{22}x_2 + ‚ãØ + A_{2n}x_n ·ú∂ ‚¶â

      ‚Äñ ‚ù≤&‚ù≥‚ãÆ ·ú∂ ‚¶â

      ‚Äñ y_n ‚ù≤&‚ù≥= A_{m1}x_1 + A_{m2}x_2 + ‚ãØ + A_{mn}x_n ·ú∂ ‚¶â

      ‚Äñ \end{aligned} ‚¶â
    ‚¶â‚¶â
‚¶â

¬∂ ‚¶ä
  ‚Äñ In this case $A ‚àà ùó•^{m √ó n}$ is a matrix. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ We call $n$ and $m$ the ‚ù¨dimensions‚ù≠ of the matrix. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ We call $n$ the ‚ù¨height‚ù≠ and $m$ the ‚ù¨width‚ù≠. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ If the height of the matrix is the same as the width of
    the matrix then we call the matrix ‚ù¨square‚ù≠. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ If the height is larger than the width, we call the matrix
    ‚ù¨tall‚ù≠. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ If the width is larger than the height, we call the matrix
    ‚ù¨wide‚ù≠. ‚¶â
‚¶â

